{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9bdcba68-a9a7-455e-9cf9-6a8932eed449","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these locations:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** (most likely):\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. Recent crashes appear here within seconds.\n\n2. **Console.app** — open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\n3. **Core dumps** (if enabled):\n   ```bash\n   # Check/enable core dumps\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   # Cores go to /cores/core.<pid>\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n   Core dumps are disabled by default on macOS and require SIP adjustments on newer versions.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report in `DiagnosticReports` is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries without any extra setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83a56b2d-6a3f-4e7b-b364-be3b823cd43e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":283,"requestId":"DA00:20684E:730DA4B:7BAB29F:6A03D866"},"id":"b589b3e5-13f6-4860-a02e-d0675c4dc1cb","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:48:30.517Z","parentId":"cee81547-6610-48d9-aac1-6c62eb35dc8a"}
